passages.text: EUROPE | Aerospace & Defense Electronics
What You Need to Know and - Rheinmetall CEO Comments, 737 Rate, GE Strike

In this document, we present the key news impacting the European A&D sector. Today, we explore: Rheinmetall's Unterluss opening, Lockheed missile production, NVL potential takeover, Ryanair expects Boeing to boost 737 MAX rate to 42/mo by October, and 600 UAW workers strike across two GE facilities.

Rheinmetall CEO Armin Papperger spoke at the opening of its new Unterluss facility yesterday, stating that the facility will be the largest ammunition site in Europe at full capacity. He also noted that similar factories could be built at a similar pace in other NATO countries to contribute to a "pan- European defense ecosystem". The Unterluss facility is expected to produce 25,000 rounds of ammunition this year, ramping to a capacity of 350,000 p.a. by 2027. Alongside this, Romania signed a framework agreement with Rheinmetall to build a munitions ignition powder factory for €535m, the country's industry minister said on Wednesday. Furthermore, WirtschaftWoche reported that Lockheed Martin is seeking to have Rheinmetall manufacture missiles in Germany, with Lockheed's Europe head saying "we are already actively discussing additional manufacturing - including for ATACMS and Hellfire missiles". Finally, Bild reported that Rheinmetall wants to take over German shipbuilder Naval Vessels Luerssen (NVL), with the board to consider the purchase in the coming weeks. Mr Papperger responded to the reports saying the company is always interested in expanding its portfolio.

The Unterluss facility should be key in ramping up ammunition to the current production targets, and, as with the Bulgaria factory announcement yesterday (our thoughts here), highlights Rheinmetall's capability in ramping up in W&A. On missile production, we continue to see the JV as a smart method to quickly expand into an area with long- term growth potential. The JV is targeting a production capacity of 10,000 missiles p.a. with production starting in 2027. On NVL, Mr Papperger highlighted on the Q2 25 call that the company was currently in negotiations in the naval segment, with the intention to "create really a big business" in order to fill current portfolio gaps. Rheinmetall is targeting to acquire at least one company annually, with >1bn of sales.

Ryanair CEO Michael O'Leary told journalists on Wednesday that he expects Boeing to boost its 737 MAX production rate to 42/mo from 38/mo by October. Mr O- Leary made the comments following discussions with Beine Commercial airplane head Stephanie Pope on Wednesday.

Mr O'Leary's estimate for 42/mo in October relies upon the FAA raising the current production cap imposed at 88/mo, which is expected to be discussed later this year. Our US colleagues currently estimate an average rate of 36/m in 2025 and 45/mo in 2026. In our view, progress on the MAX ramp- up, and turn the LEAP, would be supportive for Safran on the OE side, while we continue to expect to see solid aftermarket trends.
The UAW President announced on Wednesday that over 600 workers across the Evendale, Ohio, and Erlanger, Kentucky, GE Aerospace sites will go on strike after failing to reach a new contract agreement.
Chloe Lemarie, CFA \* | Equity Analyst

We see the strike's impact on the broader LEAP supply chain to be fairly limited. The 600 workers represent c. \(1\%\) of the total 53,000 strong global workforce. Furthermore, the Evendale site is more focused on marine and industrial engines.
Unless specified, no company has commented on the press reports mentioned.
